The Telegraph - Calcutta : International

 Monday, September 06, 2004 

 Nepal peace rally

 Kathmandu, Sept. 5 (PTI): About 4,000 people from various religious groups took out a peace rally here to denounce the brutal killing of 12 Nepalis by militants in Iraq as a curfew imposed on the capital Kathmandu following violent protests over the slaying was eased for a total of 15 hours.

 The curfew was relaxed from 4 am to 2 pm and again from 5 pm to 10 pm for the convenience of the public, a government notice said.

 The notice said curfew in Kathmandu and Lalitpur municipalities was relaxed due to improvement in the law and order situation.

 Business activity has almost returned to normal, transport services have resumed and many offices have opened. However, schools and colleges remain closed due to the curfew.

 Demonstrators from various religious groups including from the World Hindu Federation and Nepal Muslim Ittehad Organisation took part in a peace rally in Kathmandu this morning to denounce the killing of the 12 Nepalis. 

 Meanwhile, a delegation of various recruiting agencies met Prime Minister Sher Bahadur Deuba and sought compensation for losses suffered during Wednesdays clashes when an angry mob vandalised their offices.




